Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have equated the earthquakes, tsunami and nuclear disaster in Japan to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The similarity is quite clear: each of these activities generates huge profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the way to prevent their reoccurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with usually harmless design flaws, caused the shutdown of cooling water flow in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
In the case of financial markets, an unexpected collapse of real estate values, combined with design flaws in the derivatives and repos markets, damaged the ability of major financial institutions to honor their debts.
Although the basic risks originate outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, overinvestment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design flaws and a lack of luck ensured that the systems could not contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – went bankrupt, causing a credit freeze in the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand fairly well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
We cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives that shook the global economy.
At Fukushima, workers are bravely trying to stop the radiation leaks.
On the other hand, for derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating similar derivatives and financial structures, above the same errors that are still active.
Financial actors use financial products to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of euro fluctuation but does not want the risk on the yen, while for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to provide euros on June 1st, and the second promises to provide yens.
If a currency loses value compared to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bills or mortgage debts, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the name "repo," which is an abbreviation for the English verb repurchase – or to buy back, ed.
The problem is that the cash from these short-term repos represents a large part of the balance sheets of the largest financial institutions, which implies that even small financial tremors can heavily affect them.
Some institutions may then find themselves without repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, like Bear Stearns.
Individually, derivatives or repo transactions are hardly blameworthy.
Each separately legitimately transfers risk to those better able to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when used excessively by institutions that are systemically vital, they can explode the financial system, due to its design flaws.
Even today, approximately 70% of the liabilities of major US financial firms consist of very short-term loans, such as repos payable the next day.
In the United States, the main design flaws lie in bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in the case of bankruptcy.
For example, investors who hold derivative or repo contracts with weakened financial institutions can seize the company's assets before – and at the expense of – its normal creditors. In doing so, they can decide the company's fate, whereas, with a little more time, the company in question could have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because derivative and repo investors end up at the head of the repayment line in so many ways, they have less incentive to encourage market discipline by closely examining the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid, anyway.
After all, someone has to be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because derivatives and repo exemptions place these actors in the forefront in case of failure.
Normally, one would expect that others would therefore have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor that comes next in line is often the U.S. government, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions. However, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it often sticks to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The U.S. Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw in the major overhaul of finance that it adopted last summer through the Dodd Frank bill.
But he didn’t grasp it.
If derivatives, repos, and credit-default swaps (credit-event derivatives, note) investors did not receive preferential treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would more often insist that their counterparties be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk generated by ultra-low capitalizations when it was essentially the money of the U.S. government; they would be less inclined to do so if it was their own money they were risking.
The public perceives risks of the Fukushima type and derivative-related risks differently.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are striking, causing a slowdown in the sector that must deal with security concerns.
But the derivatives and repo markets present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to discuss and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and contempt, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own fate with the legislative body.
Regarding risks of the Fukushima type, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain risks related to earthquakes and tsunamis through passive cooling systems.
It is now considered possible to design nuclear power plants capable of keeping fuel rods cold even in the event of a complete power outage.
On the other hand, little significant progress has been made so far in preventing the damage that the priority of derivatives and repo transactions in the event of failure could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require end users (such as oil companies using derivatives to hedge against unexpected price changes in oil) and others to post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main issue: the weak incentives for market discipline among major financial institutions.
It's as if we are responding to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully place on derivatives and repo investors the risk associated with their decisions when they engage in transactions with financial institutions that are systemically vital.
We instead survived the 2008 financial tsunami only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same flawed design.
